The name of [[Denali|the highest mountain in North America]] became a [[Geographical renaming|subject of dispute]] in 1975, when the [[Alaska Legislature]] asked the [[U.S. federal government]] to officially change its name from "Mount McKinley" to "Denali". The mountain had been unofficially named Mount McKinley in 1896 by a gold prospector and officially by the federal government in 1917 to commemorate [[William McKinley]], who was [[President of the United States]] from 1897 until [[Assassination of William McKinley|his assassination in 1901]].

The name ''Denali'' is based on the [[Koyukon language|Koyukon]] name of the mountain, {{lang|koy|Deenaalee}} ('the high one').<ref name="Shem-Pete"/><ref name="IBT-Glum">{{cite news|last=Glum|first=Julia|title=What Does Denali Mean? Mount McKinley's New Name Traditionally Defined As 'The High One'|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/what-does-denali-mean-mount-mckinleys-new-name-traditionally-defined-high-one-2075235|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=August 31, 2015|access-date=September 1, 2015}}{{unreliable source?|date=September 2015}}<!--IBT now suddenly an expert source on obscure languages--></ref> The [[Koyukon]] are a people of [[Alaskan Athabaskans]] (also known as Dena), who settled in the interior area north of the mountain.<ref name=Shem-Pete>{{cite book | title=Shem Pete's Alaska: The Territory of the Upper Cook Inlet Dena'ina | first1=James | last1=Kari | first2=James A. | last2=Fall | first3=Shem | last3=Pete | publisher=University of Alaska Press | location=Fairbanks, AK | date=August 1, 2003 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y9oUBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA211 | pages=211–213 | isbn=978-1-889963-57-0 | access-date=September 1, 2015}}</ref>{{efn|name=ADNMartinson|[[James Kari]] of the [[Alaska Native Language Center]] writes in ''Shem Pete's Alaska'', the "name 'Denali' is based upon the [[Koyukon language|Koyukon]] place name as used by the people north of the mountain." Kari explains that "the name 'Denali' does not mean 'The Great One', as is commonly cited, but is instead based upon this verb theme meaning 'high' or 'tall{{' "}}.<ref name="ADN-Martinson">{{cite web | title=McKinley no more: North America's tallest peak to be renamed Denali | first=Erica | last=Martinson | work=[[Alaska Dispatch News]] | date=August 30, 2015 | url=http://www.adn.com/article/20150830/mckinley-no-more-americas-tallest-peak-be-renamed-denali | access-date=September 1, 2015}}</ref>}}

In 1975, the state of Alaska requested that the mountain be officially recognized as Denali, as it was still the common name used in the state and was traditional among Alaska Native peoples. This change action was repeatedly blocked by members of the [[United States congressional delegations from Ohio|congressional delegation from Ohio]], the home state of the mountain's presidential namesake. 

In August 2015, [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Sally Jewell]] announced that the name would officially be changed to Denali in all federal documents.<ref name="OrderNo3337">{{cite press release|author=[[United States Department of the Interior|U.S. Department of the Interior]]/[[Sally Jewell]]|title=Order No. 3337: Change of the Name of Mount McKinley to Denali|url=https://www.doi.gov/sites/doi.gov/files/elips/documents/3337%20-%20Changing%20the%20Name%20of%20Mount%20McKinley%20to%20Denali.pdf|publisher=U.S. Department of the Interior|date=August 28, 2015|access-date=August 14, 2023}}</ref><ref name="OldNameReturns">{{cite news|last=Campbell|first=Jon|title=Old Name Officially Returns to Nation's Highest Peak|url=https://www.usgs.gov/news/old-name-officially-returns-nations-highest-peak|publisher=[[United States Board on Geographic Names|U.S. Board on Geographic Names]] ([[United States Geological Survey|U.S. Geological Survey]])|date=August 30, 2015|access-date=August 10, 2020}}</ref> While on an Alaskan visit in the first week of September 2015, President [[Barack Obama]] announced the renaming of the mountain.<ref name=Davidson />  The Obama Administration's proposal was met with immediate criticism from the entire US Congressional delegation from Ohio.<ref name=NBC-Schuppe>{{cite web | title=Mt. McKinley to Denali: How A Mountain's Renaming Got Tied Up in Politics | first=Jon | last=Schuppe | work=NBC News|date=August 31, 2015|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/mckinley-denali-how-mountains-renaming-got-tied-politics-n418811 | access-date=September 1, 2015}}</ref>

